<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" ?>
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="SpoonTrack.Views.HelpPage"
             Title="Help"
             BackgroundColor="#1E1E1E">

    <ScrollView>
        <VerticalStackLayout Padding="20" Spacing="25">

            <Label Text="‚ùì Help and Tutorial"
                   FontSize="28"
                   FontAttributes="Bold"
                   TextColor="#E0E0E0" />

            <!-- Spoon Theory -->
            <Frame BackgroundColor="#2A2A2A" 
                   BorderColor="#3A3A3A"
                   CornerRadius="15"
                   Padding="20">
                <VerticalStackLayout Spacing="10">
                    <Label Text="ü•Ñ What is Spoon Theory?"
                           FontSize="20"
                           FontAttributes="Bold"
                           TextColor="#4CAF50" />

                    <Label TextColor="#E0E0E0" FontSize="16">
                        <Label.Text>
                            Spoon Theory was created by Christine Miserandino to explain chronic illness energy limits.

Each "spoon" = unit of energy

Healthy person: ~50 spoons/day
Person with ME/CFS: 5-12 spoons/day

Activities cost spoons:
- Shower: -2 spoons
- Cook meal: -3 spoons
- Work 2h: -4 spoons
- Go shopping: -4 spoons

When you run out = CRASH (PEM)
                        </Label.Text>
                    </Label>
                </VerticalStackLayout>
            </Frame>

            <!-- Como usar -->
            <Frame BackgroundColor="#2A2A2A" 
                   BorderColor="#3A3A3A"
                   CornerRadius="15"
                   Padding="20">
                <VerticalStackLayout Spacing="10">
                    <Label Text="üì± How to Use SpoonTrack"
                           FontSize="20"
                           FontAttributes="Bold"
                           TextColor="#2196F3" />

                    <Label TextColor="#E0E0E0" FontSize="16">
                        <Label.Text>
                            1. TODAY tab: Log daily energy (1-10 spoons)
2. PLANNING tab: Plan activities before doing them
3. CHARTS tab: See energy trends over time
4. HISTORY tab: Review past entries

Track every day to identify patterns!
                        </Label.Text>
                    </Label>
                </VerticalStackLayout>
            </Frame>

            <!-- Pacing Tips -->
            <Frame BackgroundColor="#2A2A2A" 
                   BorderColor="#3A3A3A"
                   CornerRadius="15"
                   Padding="20">
                <VerticalStackLayout Spacing="10">
                    <Label Text="‚ö° Pacing Tips"
                           FontSize="20"
                           FontAttributes="Bold"
                           TextColor="#FFC107" />

                    <Label TextColor="#E0E0E0" FontSize="16">
                        <Label.Text>
                            ‚úÖ DO:
- Stay within your spoon budget
- Rest BEFORE you crash
- Plan high-energy tasks for best days
- Save 1-2 spoons for emergencies

‚ùå DON'T:
- Push through fatigue
- Do everything on "good days"
- Ignore warning signs
- Compare yourself to healthy people

Remember: Pacing prevents PEM!
                        </Label.Text>
                    </Label>
                </VerticalStackLayout>
            </Frame>

            <!-- PEM Warning -->
            <Frame BackgroundColor="#F44336" 
                   CornerRadius="15"
                   Padding="20">
                <VerticalStackLayout Spacing="10">
                    <Label Text="‚ö†Ô∏è What is PEM?"
                           FontSize="20"
                           FontAttributes="Bold"
                           TextColor="White" />

                    <Label TextColor="White" FontSize="16">
                        <Label.Text>
                            Post-Exertional Malaise (PEM) = crash after overexertion

Symptoms:
- Extreme fatigue for days/weeks
- Worsened pain, brain fog
- Flu-like symptoms
- Can't recover with rest alone

Prevention is KEY: Stay within limits!
                        </Label.Text>
                    </Label>
                </VerticalStackLayout>
            </Frame>

        </VerticalStackLayout>
    </ScrollView>
</ContentPage>